AB  - This paper deals with estimation of input-oriented (IO) technical inefficiency using a stochastic production frontier model. Econometrically the model is similar to a class of models that arise in specifying technical inefficiency in cost-minimizing and profit-maximizing frameworks. The standard maximum likelihood (ML) method that is used to estimate output-oriented (OO) technical efficiency cannot be applied to estimate these models. We use a simulated ML approach to estimate the IO production function and compare results from the IO and OO models, mainly to emphasize the point that estimated efficiency, returns to scale, technical change, etc., differ depending on whether one uses the model with IO or OO technical inefficiency.
